    INSERT INTO lessons (module_id, title, description, content, order_index, duration_minutes, brief_content, action_items, resources) VALUES
    (v_module_id, 'Understanding Brand Architecture', 'Learn the fundamentals of brand architecture and positioning for Indian startups.',
    'Complete guide to brand architecture fundamentals.', 1, 45,
    'Brand architecture is the organizational structure of your brand portfolio, defining how your company, products, and services relate to each other. For Indian startups, getting this right from day one prevents costly rebranding later.

The three primary brand architecture models are: Branded House (like Tata - where the master brand dominates), House of Brands (like HUL - where individual brands operate independently), and Endorsed Brands (like Mahindra - where the parent brand provides credibility backing).

For early-stage startups, the Branded House model typically works best. It concentrates marketing spend, builds equity faster, and simplifies decision-making. As you scale to multiple distinct product lines, you can evolve to hybrid models.

Your brand positioning statement should answer: Who is your target audience? What category do you compete in? What is your unique benefit? What is the reason to believe? Indian consumers particularly value trust signals, heritage (even for new brands, through founder story), and value-for-money positioning.

The Indian market has unique considerations: regional diversity means your brand must translate across 22 official languages without losing meaning. Colors, symbols, and numbers carry different connotations across regions. For example, red signifies prosperity in many parts of India but should be used carefully in communications around financial losses.

Brand positioning in India often succeeds when it connects to cultural values: family, aspiration, respect for expertise, and the journey of transformation. Brands like Amul have mastered this by becoming part of the cultural conversation.

Start by documenting your brand foundation: mission, vision, values, and positioning statement. These become the filter through which all brand decisions flow. Review them quarterly as your startup evolves, but avoid frequent pivots that confuse your audience.',
    '[{"task": "Document your brand mission, vision, and values in a single-page brand foundation document", "priority": "high"}, {"task": "Analyze 5 successful Indian startup brands and identify their architecture model", "priority": "medium"}, {"task": "Create your brand positioning statement using the standard framework", "priority": "high"}, {"task": "Test your brand name pronunciation and meaning across 5 major Indian languages", "priority": "medium"}]',
    '[{"title": "Brand Architecture Guide by Interbrand", "url": "https://interbrand.com/thinking/", "type": "guide"}, {"title": "India Brand Equity Foundation Resources", "url": "https://www.ibef.org/", "type": "resource"}, {"title": "YourStory Brand Building Stories", "url": "https://yourstory.com/", "type": "publication"}, {"title": "Pitch.Link Brand Strategy Templates", "url": "https://pitch.link/", "type": "tool"}]'),

    (v_module_id, 'Competitive Brand Analysis', 'Master techniques to analyze competitor brands and identify market opportunities.',
    'Deep dive into competitive brand analysis methods.', 2, 40,
    'Competitive brand analysis in India requires understanding both direct competitors and adjacent players who might enter your space. The Indian startup ecosystem has seen rapid commoditization in many sectors, making differentiation crucial.

Start by mapping your competitive landscape across four dimensions: Direct competitors (same product, same audience), Indirect competitors (different product, same need), Potential disruptors (adjacent players who could pivot), and Aspirational benchmarks (brands you admire, even from different industries).

For each competitor, analyze their brand presence: visual identity consistency, messaging themes, media coverage patterns, social media engagement, and customer sentiment. Tools like Social Blade, Similarweb, and Google Trends provide quantitative data; manual review of their communications provides qualitative insights.

In India, also track regional competitors who might be dominant in specific states but absent nationally. Many successful Indian startups started by dominating one region before expanding. Understanding these regional dynamics helps identify white spaces.

Create a brand perception map plotting competitors on axes relevant to your category (e.g., premium vs. value, traditional vs. modern, specialist vs. generalist). Identify where clusters form and where gaps exist. Your positioning should ideally occupy a defensible gap rather than competing head-on with established players.

Analyze competitor PR and media strategy: Which publications feature them? Who are their spokespersons? What themes do they emphasize? This reveals opportunities to differentiate your narrative. If competitors focus heavily on technology, perhaps emphasizing customer outcomes creates distinction.

Monitor competitor brand changes through trademark filings (search.ipindia.gov.in), company announcements, and job postings (PR or brand manager hires signal upcoming campaigns).

Document findings in a competitive brand intelligence dashboard updated monthly. Include share of voice metrics, sentiment analysis, and emerging narrative themes.',
    '[{"task": "Create a competitive landscape map with 10+ players including regional competitors", "priority": "high"}, {"task": "Set up Google Alerts and social listening for top 5 competitors", "priority": "high"}, {"task": "Build a brand perception positioning map for your category", "priority": "medium"}, {"task": "Analyze competitor media coverage from the past 6 months to identify themes", "priority": "medium"}]',
    '[{"title": "Similarweb Competitive Analysis", "url": "https://www.similarweb.com/", "type": "tool"}, {"title": "Indian Trademark Search", "url": "https://search.ipindia.gov.in/", "type": "government"}, {"title": "Social Blade Analytics", "url": "https://socialblade.com/", "type": "tool"}, {"title": "Inc42 Startup Coverage", "url": "https://inc42.com/", "type": "publication"}]'),

    (v_module_id, 'Brand Differentiation Strategy', 'Develop unique brand differentiation that creates lasting competitive advantage.',
    'Strategies for meaningful brand differentiation.', 3, 45,
    'Brand differentiation in the crowded Indian startup ecosystem requires more than clever taglines—it demands genuine strategic choices that permeate every customer touchpoint.

The strongest differentiation comes from making trade-offs competitors are unwilling to make. Zerodha differentiated not through features but by eliminating brokerage on equity delivery trades—a trade-off traditional brokers avoided. This created a clear, defensible position.

Seven paths to brand differentiation: 1) Category creation (define a new space you can own), 2) Customer segment focus (serve an underserved niche deeply), 3) Business model innovation (change how value is delivered), 4) Cultural connection (embed in Indian cultural moments), 5) Technology leadership (own a technical capability), 6) Experience design (create distinctive interactions), 7) Values and purpose (stand for something meaningful).

For Indian markets, differentiation often succeeds through localization that global players cannot match. This includes vernacular-first experiences, hyperlocal understanding, India-specific feature development, and cultural nuance in communications.

Test your differentiation using the "only" statement: "We are the only [category] that [differentiation] for [audience]." If multiple competitors can truthfully make the same claim, you need sharper differentiation.

Sustainable differentiation typically requires operational embedding. If your differentiation is just messaging, competitors copy it within months. If it requires fundamental operational changes, it becomes more defensible.

Document your differentiation strategy with specific proof points. Abstract claims ("best quality") mean nothing; specific, verifiable claims build credibility. Instead of "best customer service," say "90-second average response time with 97% first-contact resolution."

Review differentiation quarterly. As competitors respond and markets evolve, what was differentiating becomes table stakes. Continuous innovation in differentiation prevents commoditization.',
    '[{"task": "Complete the only statement exercise for your brand", "priority": "high"}, {"task": "Identify 3 trade-offs your brand makes that competitors avoid", "priority": "high"}, {"task": "Document 5 specific proof points supporting your differentiation claims", "priority": "medium"}, {"task": "Create a differentiation roadmap showing evolution over 24 months", "priority": "medium"}]',
    '[{"title": "Differentiation Strategy - HBR", "url": "https://hbr.org/topic/subject/competitive-strategy", "type": "publication"}, {"title": "Blue Ocean Strategy Tools", "url": "https://www.blueoceanstrategy.com/tools/", "type": "framework"}, {"title": "Economic Times Brand Equity", "url": "https://brandequity.economictimes.indiatimes.com/", "type": "publication"}, {"title": "Positioning by Ries & Trout", "url": "https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/760025.Positioning", "type": "book"}]');

