    INSERT INTO lessons (module_id, title, description, content, order_index, duration_minutes, brief_content, action_items, resources) VALUES
    (v_module_id, 'Logo Design Principles', 'Master the principles of effective logo design for brand recognition.',
    'Comprehensive guide to logo design for startups.', 1, 45,
    'Your logo is the most visible element of your brand identity, appearing on everything from business cards to billboard advertisements. In India''s visually cluttered environment, a distinctive logo helps your brand cut through noise.

Effective startup logos follow key principles: Simplicity (works at small sizes and in single color), Memorability (distinctive enough to recall), Timelessness (avoids trendy elements that date quickly), Versatility (works across media and applications), and Appropriateness (fits industry and audience expectations).

The logo development process begins with strategic inputs: brand positioning, target audience, competitive landscape, and intended usage scenarios. Brief designers thoroughly—good logos emerge from good briefs, not just good designers.

Logo types include: Wordmarks (text-based, like Google), Lettermarks (initials, like IBM), Pictorial marks (icons, like Apple), Abstract marks (geometric, like Airbnb), Mascots (characters, like Amul), and Combination marks (text plus symbol). For startups with limited brand awareness, combination marks typically work best as they build name recognition while the symbol builds memorability.

In India, consider Devanagari or regional script versions of your logo for vernacular communications. This shows cultural respect and improves recognition in regional markets. Ensure your logo works in both scripts without forced translations.

Color psychology matters: Blue conveys trust (banking, healthcare), Green signals growth and sustainability, Orange represents energy and enthusiasm, Yellow evokes optimism. However, avoid over-relying on color—your logo should work in pure black and white.

Production requirements: Vector format master files (AI, EPS, SVG), multiple color versions (full color, single color, reversed), clear space specifications, minimum size requirements, and usage guidelines documenting incorrect applications.

Budget realistically: Quality logo design from experienced designers costs ₹50,000-₹2,00,000. Investing in professional design pays dividends through years of consistent usage.',
    '[{"task": "Create a comprehensive logo design brief documenting strategy and requirements", "priority": "high"}, {"task": "Research 20 competitor and aspirational logos analyzing what works", "priority": "medium"}, {"task": "Get quotes from 3-5 professional logo designers or agencies", "priority": "high"}, {"task": "Develop a logo evaluation rubric with scoring criteria", "priority": "medium"}]',
    '[{"title": "LogoLounge Trends Report", "url": "https://www.logolounge.com/", "type": "resource"}, {"title": "Behance Logo Design Inspiration", "url": "https://www.behance.net/search/projects?search=logo%20design%20india", "type": "inspiration"}, {"title": "Brand New by UnderConsideration", "url": "https://www.underconsideration.com/brandnew/", "type": "publication"}, {"title": "Indian Graphic Design Resources", "url": "https://www.kyoorius.com/", "type": "community"}]'),

    (v_module_id, 'Color and Typography Systems', 'Build cohesive color palettes and typography hierarchies for your brand.',
    'Complete guide to brand color and typography.', 2, 40,
    'Color and typography form the visual foundation of your brand system, creating instant recognition and emotional connection. In India''s diverse visual landscape, systematic approaches ensure consistency across touchpoints.

Color system development starts with a primary brand color that embodies your positioning. This anchors your palette. Add secondary colors (2-3) for variety in communications, accent colors for calls-to-action and highlights, and neutral colors (grays, blacks, whites) for text and backgrounds.

Define color specifications precisely: Pantone references for print, CMYK for offset printing, RGB and HEX for digital, and specific paint codes for physical applications. Indian printing varies in quality—providing exact specifications improves consistency.

Cultural color considerations in India: White can signify mourning in some contexts; saffron has religious and political associations; green similarly carries religious meaning for some audiences. Test color perceptions with diverse audience samples before finalizing.

Accessibility matters: Ensure sufficient contrast ratios (WCAG 2.1 guidelines require 4.5:1 for normal text). Color-blind users represent 8% of males—never rely on color alone to convey information.

Typography selection: Choose primary and secondary typefaces that complement each other. Your primary typeface carries most communications; secondary provides contrast for headlines or accents. For Indian markets, ensure your type system includes Devanagari and regional script support.

License typography appropriately: Google Fonts provides free options; premium typefaces require commercial licenses (often ₹10,000-₹50,000+ for comprehensive rights). Indian Type Foundry and Ek Type offer excellent Indic typography.

Establish type hierarchy: Heading styles (H1-H6), body text, captions, labels. Define sizes, weights, line heights, and letter spacing for each. This systematization enables consistent application across teams and vendors.

Document everything in a digital brand guidelines document with specific applications and examples.',
    '[{"task": "Define your complete color palette with all technical specifications", "priority": "high"}, {"task": "Select and license primary and secondary typefaces including Indic scripts", "priority": "high"}, {"task": "Create type hierarchy specifications for digital and print applications", "priority": "medium"}, {"task": "Test color accessibility using WCAG contrast checkers", "priority": "medium"}]',
    '[{"title": "Indian Type Foundry", "url": "https://www.indiantypefoundry.com/", "type": "resource"}, {"title": "Ek Type Foundry", "url": "https://ektype.in/", "type": "resource"}, {"title": "Coolors Palette Generator", "url": "https://coolors.co/", "type": "tool"}, {"title": "WebAIM Contrast Checker", "url": "https://webaim.org/resources/contrastchecker/", "type": "tool"}]'),

    (v_module_id, 'Brand Guidelines Documentation', 'Create comprehensive brand guidelines that ensure consistent application.',
    'Building brand guidelines that work.', 3, 45,
    'Brand guidelines document your visual identity system, ensuring consistent application across teams, vendors, and touchpoints. In growing startups where multiple people create branded materials, guidelines prevent brand drift.

Essential brand guidelines sections: Brand story and positioning (strategic foundation), Logo specifications (versions, clear space, minimum sizes, incorrect usage), Color system (primary, secondary, accent with specifications), Typography (typefaces, hierarchy, usage rules), Imagery style (photography, illustration, iconography direction), Voice and tone (how the brand communicates), and Applications (business cards, presentations, social media templates).

Create guidelines at appropriate complexity for your stage. Early startups need functional guidelines (10-20 pages) covering essentials. Enterprise brand books spanning 100+ pages are overkill until you have complex, distributed teams.

Digital-first guidelines using tools like Frontify, Brandpad, or Notion ensure guidelines remain accessible and updateable. PDF guidelines become outdated quickly as brands evolve.

Practical application examples make guidelines useful. Instead of abstract rules, show real executions: "Here''s how to lay out a LinkedIn post," "Here''s the email signature format." Templates accelerate correct application.

Include a section on common mistakes with examples. Showing incorrect usage (low-resolution logos, wrong colors, unauthorized modifications) helps teams avoid errors.

Version control your guidelines with change logs. When updates occur, communicate them to all stakeholders with clear effective dates.

Complement guidelines with template libraries: Presentation templates (Google Slides/PowerPoint), Social media templates (Canva/Figma), Email signatures, Business cards and letterhead, and Proposal templates.

Make guidelines enforceable by assigning brand governance responsibility. Designate who reviews materials before publication and establish approval workflows.',
    '[{"task": "Create a comprehensive brand guidelines document covering all essential sections", "priority": "high"}, {"task": "Build a template library for common brand applications", "priority": "high"}, {"task": "Set up a digital brand portal for guidelines access", "priority": "medium"}, {"task": "Define brand governance process with approval workflows", "priority": "medium"}]',
    '[{"title": "Frontify Brand Management Platform", "url": "https://www.frontify.com/", "type": "tool"}, {"title": "Brand Guidelines Examples", "url": "https://brandingstyleguides.com/", "type": "inspiration"}, {"title": "Canva Brand Kit", "url": "https://www.canva.com/brand-management/", "type": "tool"}, {"title": "Figma Brand Templates", "url": "https://www.figma.com/community/tag/brand%20guidelines/files", "type": "resource"}]');

