    INSERT INTO lessons (module_id, title, description, content, order_index, duration_minutes, brief_content, action_items, resources) VALUES
    (v_module_id, 'Defining Brand Voice', 'Create a distinctive voice that sets your brand apart in communications.',
    'Comprehensive guide to brand voice development.', 1, 45,
    'Brand voice is the consistent expression of your brand through words. While visual identity creates recognition, voice builds personality and emotional connection. In India''s relationship-driven business culture, authentic voice matters particularly.

Voice characteristics exist on spectrums: Formal to casual, Serious to playful, Respectful to irreverent, Enthusiastic to matter-of-fact. Position your brand on each spectrum based on audience expectations and brand personality.

Develop voice through three components: Voice (consistent personality—who we are), Tone (contextual adaptation—varies by situation), and Language (specific vocabulary, phrases, and structures).

For Indian audiences, voice considerations include: Formality levels vary by region and generation—younger urban audiences accept casual; older or traditional segments expect respect. Code-switching between English and Hindi (Hinglish) can feel authentic or forced depending on execution. Regional language communications require native speakers, not translations.

Create voice guidelines with examples: "We say this, not that" comparisons clarify abstract principles. Show the same message in correct and incorrect versions. Include examples across contexts: website copy, customer service, social media, formal communications.

Voice should extend to all touchpoints: Error messages, confirmation emails, hold music, chatbot responses, invoice descriptions. Every word is a brand experience.

Test voice with real audience samples. What reads as "friendly" internally might feel "unprofessional" to customers. Qualitative research validates voice direction before broad implementation.

Document voice in your brand guidelines with sufficient examples for writers to internalize patterns. Consider creating a word bank of preferred terminology and phrases to avoid.

Train all customer-facing teams on voice. Customer service representatives, salespeople, and social media managers need voice education, not just guidelines documents.',
    '[{"task": "Define your brand voice characteristics across 5 key spectrums", "priority": "high"}, {"task": "Create a voice guidelines document with 20+ this vs that examples", "priority": "high"}, {"task": "Develop a preferred terminology word bank for your brand", "priority": "medium"}, {"task": "Conduct voice testing with 10 representative customers", "priority": "medium"}]',
    '[{"title": "Mailchimp Voice and Tone Guide", "url": "https://styleguide.mailchimp.com/voice-and-tone/", "type": "example"}, {"title": "Content Design London Resources", "url": "https://contentdesign.london/", "type": "resource"}, {"title": "Writer Style Guide Tool", "url": "https://writer.com/", "type": "tool"}, {"title": "Grammarly Business", "url": "https://www.grammarly.com/business", "type": "tool"}]'),

    (v_module_id, 'Messaging Framework Development', 'Build a comprehensive messaging framework for consistent communication.',
    'Creating scalable messaging architecture.', 2, 45,
    'A messaging framework provides structured content that teams use to communicate consistently about your brand, products, and value proposition. It transforms brand strategy into usable communication tools.

The messaging hierarchy flows from: Mission statement (why you exist), Vision statement (where you are going), Value proposition (what you offer and why it matters), Key messages (primary themes you communicate), Supporting messages (proof points and details), and Specific claims (feature-level communications).

Your core messaging platform should include: Elevator pitch (30 seconds), Boilerplate (company description for press), Tagline (memorable phrase), Key differentiators (3-5 primary distinctions), and Audience-specific messaging (variations for different segments).

In India, develop messaging variations for: Decision makers vs. users vs. influencers, Enterprise vs. SMB vs. consumer, Regional and language variations, Industry vertical customizations, and Funding stage communications (investor messaging).

Message testing validates resonance. Use methods like: A/B testing headlines and value propositions, Qualitative interviews exploring message interpretation, Survey-based message ranking exercises, and Social media engagement analysis.

Common messaging mistakes in Indian startups: Over-claiming without proof points, Using jargon audiences do not understand, Translating English messaging literally into regional languages, Ignoring cultural context in examples and references, and Generic messaging that could describe any competitor.

Create a messaging matrix mapping messages to audiences, channels, and contexts. This tool helps teams select appropriate messaging for specific situations.

Document messaging in accessible formats: One-page quick reference for sales calls, Detailed playbook for content creators, and FAQ responses for support teams. Update quarterly based on market feedback and competitive evolution.',
    '[{"task": "Develop complete messaging hierarchy from mission through specific claims", "priority": "high"}, {"task": "Create audience-specific messaging variations for 5 key segments", "priority": "high"}, {"task": "Build a messaging matrix mapping content to audiences and channels", "priority": "medium"}, {"task": "Test core messages with representative customers through interviews", "priority": "medium"}]',
    '[{"title": "Messaging Framework Templates", "url": "https://www.productmarketingalliance.com/", "type": "resource"}, {"title": "StoryBrand Framework", "url": "https://storybrand.com/", "type": "framework"}, {"title": "Wynter Message Testing", "url": "https://wynter.com/", "type": "tool"}, {"title": "Copy.ai for Messaging Ideas", "url": "https://www.copy.ai/", "type": "tool"}]'),

    (v_module_id, 'Storytelling for Brands', 'Master the art of brand storytelling that creates emotional connections.',
    'Building narrative-driven brand communications.', 3, 40,
    'Brand storytelling transforms facts and features into narratives that create emotional connections. Indian culture has deep storytelling traditions—brands that tap into narrative structures resonate more deeply than those relying purely on rational arguments.

Effective brand stories follow archetypal structures: The Hero''s Journey (customer overcomes challenges with your help), Origin Story (how and why you started), Transformation Story (before and after your impact), David vs. Goliath (disrupting established players), and Mission Story (the change you seek in the world).

Your founder story often provides the most authentic narrative material. Why did you start this company? What personal experience revealed the problem? What obstacles did you overcome? Indian audiences particularly connect with founder journeys that mirror their own aspirations.

Story elements to develop: Characters (founders, customers, team members), Setting (the world/industry as it exists), Conflict (the problem being solved), Journey (the path to solution), and Resolution (the transformed state).

Customer stories demonstrate impact more powerfully than company claims. Collect and document customer transformation narratives. Get video testimonials showing real people sharing real results.

Story formats for different channels: Long-form for website about pages and investor decks, Medium-form for blog posts and LinkedIn articles, Short-form for social media and advertisements, and Micro-stories for testimonials and case study snippets.

Authenticity matters immensely. Indian audiences detect manufactured narratives quickly. Ground stories in verifiable truth—embellishment backfires when discovered.

Create a story library documenting: Company origin narrative, Founder personal stories, Customer transformation stories, Team member stories, Product development stories, and Impact stories with specific outcomes.

Train spokespersons to tell stories consistently. Provide story frameworks and key beats while allowing natural delivery variation.',
    '[{"task": "Document your company origin story in long, medium, and short formats", "priority": "high"}, {"task": "Collect 5 detailed customer transformation stories with testimonials", "priority": "high"}, {"task": "Create a brand story library with categorized narratives", "priority": "medium"}, {"task": "Train 3 key spokespersons on delivering brand stories", "priority": "medium"}]',
    '[{"title": "Building a StoryBrand Book", "url": "https://storybrand.com/building-a-storybrand/", "type": "book"}, {"title": "The Hero with a Thousand Faces", "url": "https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/588138.The_Hero_With_a_Thousand_Faces", "type": "book"}, {"title": "Harvard Business Review - Storytelling", "url": "https://hbr.org/topic/subject/storytelling", "type": "publication"}, {"title": "Lumen5 Video Storytelling", "url": "https://lumen5.com/", "type": "tool"}]');

