    INSERT INTO lessons (module_id, title, description, content, order_index, duration_minutes, brief_content, action_items, resources) VALUES
    (v_module_id, 'Understanding Indian Media Landscape', 'Navigate the complex Indian media ecosystem for effective PR.',
    'Complete guide to Indian media landscape.', 1, 45,
    'India''s media landscape is vast and fragmented, offering numerous opportunities for startup coverage but requiring strategic navigation. Understanding media tiers, publication focuses, and journalist interests enables effective PR.

Media tiers in India: Tier 1 (national reach, high credibility): Economic Times, Mint, Business Standard, Financial Express, Hindustan Times, Times of India, Indian Express. Tier 2 (strong reach, specific audiences): YourStory, Inc42, Entrepreneur India, Business Today, Forbes India, Outlook Business. Tier 3 (niche or regional): TechCircle, MediaNama, VCCircle, regional business publications.

Startup-focused publications to prioritize: YourStory (India''s largest startup media platform), Inc42 (startup news and analysis), Entrepreneur India (entrepreneurship focus), VCCircle (funding and deals), and TechCircle (technology deep dives).

National business publications have different angles: Economic Times covers market impact and policy, Mint focuses on analysis and trends, Business Standard emphasizes numbers and governance, and Financial Express highlights policy and sector developments.

Regional media matters enormously: Dainik Jagran, Amar Ujala, and Navbharat Times (Hindi), Ananda Bazar Patrika (Bengali), Eenadu (Telugu), Dinamalar (Tamil), Maharashtra Times (Marathi), Gujarat Samachar (Gujarati), and many more. Regional media often has higher trust and engagement than national English publications.

Television coverage: CNBC-TV18, ET Now, Zee Business, and NDTV Profit cover startup stories, particularly funding announcements and founder interviews. TV provides reach but requires strong spokespeople comfortable on camera.

Digital-first media: Many journalists maintain active social media presences, particularly on Twitter/X and LinkedIn. Following and engaging with journalists builds familiarity before pitching.

Build a comprehensive media list categorized by: Publication tier, Beat (fintech, healthtech, funding, policy), Format (news, features, analysis, opinion), and Outlet type (print, digital, broadcast).',
    '[{"task": "Build a targeted media list with 50+ relevant journalists and their beats", "priority": "high"}, {"task": "Subscribe to and regularly read top 10 publications covering your sector", "priority": "high"}, {"task": "Create Google Alerts for key journalists covering your industry", "priority": "medium"}, {"task": "Map regional media opportunities in your key geographic markets", "priority": "medium"}]',
    '[{"title": "YourStory", "url": "https://yourstory.com/", "type": "publication"}, {"title": "Inc42", "url": "https://inc42.com/", "type": "publication"}, {"title": "Economic Times Tech", "url": "https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/tech", "type": "publication"}, {"title": "Mint Startup Coverage", "url": "https://www.livemint.com/companies/start-ups", "type": "publication"}]'),

    (v_module_id, 'Building Journalist Relationships', 'Develop genuine relationships with journalists that lead to coverage.',
    'Relationship-first approach to media relations.', 2, 40,
    'Effective media relations in India are built on genuine relationships, not transactional pitching. Journalists receive hundreds of pitches daily—relationships determine whose emails get opened and read.

Start by providing value before asking for coverage. Share industry insights, connect journalists with expert sources, provide data for stories they are researching, and offer off-the-record context on market developments. Become a valuable resource, not just another pitch in their inbox.

Research journalists thoroughly before engaging: Read their recent articles to understand their interests and angle preferences, note which companies and founders they quote regularly, identify gaps in their coverage you could fill, follow their social media to understand their personality and views, and check their Twitter/X for real-time interests and discussions.

Initial outreach should be brief and valuable: Introduce yourself and your relevance to their beat, offer a specific insight or resource (not a pitch), make it easy to say yes to a quick call, and avoid immediately asking for coverage.

Build relationships through: LinkedIn connections with personalized notes, Twitter/X engagement on their posts, In-person meetings at industry events, Providing comments for their ongoing stories, and Sharing their articles with genuine appreciation.

Respect journalist boundaries: They are not friends—maintain professional relationship, Understand their deadline pressures, Never pitch during breaking news in their beat, Accept rejection gracefully without arguments, and Never go over their head to editors.

Maintain relationships between news cycles: Regular check-ins without pitches, Share relevant industry updates, Congratulate them on good stories, and Provide expert commentary when requested.

Build relationships with multiple journalists per publication. Staff changes frequently—relationships with the publication should survive individual departures.',
    '[{"task": "Identify 20 journalists who cover your sector and research each thoroughly", "priority": "high"}, {"task": "Engage meaningfully with 10 journalists on social media before any pitch", "priority": "high"}, {"task": "Offer to provide expert commentary or data for 3 journalists ongoing stories", "priority": "medium"}, {"task": "Schedule informational coffee meetings with 5 journalists with no pitch agenda", "priority": "medium"}]',
    '[{"title": "Muck Rack Journalist Database", "url": "https://muckrack.com/", "type": "tool"}, {"title": "LinkedIn Sales Navigator", "url": "https://business.linkedin.com/sales-solutions", "type": "tool"}, {"title": "Twitter Lists for Journalists", "url": "https://twitter.com/", "type": "platform"}, {"title": "PR Daily for Media Relations Tips", "url": "https://www.prdaily.com/", "type": "publication"}]'),

    (v_module_id, 'Press Kit Development', 'Create comprehensive press materials that make journalist jobs easier.',
    'Building effective press resources.', 3, 45,
    'A professional press kit provides journalists with everything they need to cover your company accurately. Making their job easier increases likelihood of coverage and ensures accurate representation.

Essential press kit components: Company overview (one-pager with key facts), Founder bios and high-resolution headshots, Company logo files (various formats and versions), Product screenshots and demo videos, Company timeline and milestones, Key metrics (if shareable), Recent press coverage samples, and Contact information for media inquiries.

Company overview should include: What you do (one paragraph), Problem you solve (market context), Solution and differentiation, Traction highlights (users, revenue, growth), Funding status, Founding date and team size, and Headquarters location.

Founder bio formats: Long-form (200-300 words) for feature profiles, Short-form (50-100 words) for news articles, Twitter-style (one line) for quick references. Include relevant background, expertise, and human interest elements.

Visual assets must be professional: High-resolution photographs (minimum 300 DPI for print), Multiple headshot options (formal, casual, action), Product imagery in various contexts, Infographics explaining your business, and B-roll video footage if available.

Host your press kit on your website with clear navigation: /press, /media, or /newsroom URL. Include a way to download all assets in a ZIP file.

Keep press kits updated: Refresh quarterly with new metrics, Update after major milestones or funding, Add recent coverage clips, and Archive outdated information.

Create embargo-specific materials: When sharing news under embargo, provide complete coverage packages including quotes, images, and background that journalists need to file stories immediately when embargo lifts.

Consider creating different press kit versions: Quick kit (one-pager for immediate needs), Standard kit (comprehensive company package), and Story-specific kits (for major announcements).',
    '[{"task": "Create a complete press kit with all essential components", "priority": "high"}, {"task": "Set up a /press page on your website with downloadable assets", "priority": "high"}, {"task": "Arrange professional headshot photography for founding team", "priority": "medium"}, {"task": "Create product demo video suitable for media use", "priority": "medium"}]',
    '[{"title": "Press Kit Examples - Notion Template", "url": "https://www.notion.so/templates/press-kit", "type": "template"}, {"title": "Dropbox Paper Press Kit Template", "url": "https://www.dropbox.com/paper", "type": "tool"}, {"title": "Canva Press Kit Templates", "url": "https://www.canva.com/templates/?query=press-kit", "type": "template"}, {"title": "High Resolution Stock for Press", "url": "https://unsplash.com/", "type": "resource"}]');

