    INSERT INTO lessons (module_id, title, description, content, order_index, duration_minutes, brief_content, action_items, resources) VALUES
    (v_module_id, 'Crisis Prevention and Preparedness', 'Build systems and plans to prevent and prepare for brand crises.',
    'Proactive crisis management fundamentals.', 1, 45,
    'Every startup will eventually face a crisis—the question is when, not if. Data breaches, product failures, executive misconduct, customer complaints going viral, regulatory issues—crises take many forms. Preparation determines whether crises become minor setbacks or existential threats.

Crisis prevention starts with risk identification: Operational risks (product failures, outages, quality issues), Reputation risks (executive behavior, company culture issues), Financial risks (funding gaps, payment defaults), Legal risks (compliance violations, IP disputes), Security risks (data breaches, hacks), and External risks (economic downturns, regulatory changes).

For each identified risk, develop: Early warning indicators to monitor, Preventive measures to reduce likelihood, Response playbooks for if they occur, and Communication templates ready for adaptation.

Build a crisis communication team before crises hit: Executive sponsor (CEO or founder for serious crises), Communications lead (owns messaging and media), Legal counsel (reviews statements, advises on liability), Operations lead (fixes underlying issues), Customer success lead (frontline customer communication), and External advisors (PR agency, legal firm on retainer).

Create a crisis communication plan documenting: Team roles and contact information, Decision-making authority and escalation paths, Stakeholder communication priorities, Holding statements for common crisis types, Media response protocols, and Social media monitoring and response procedures.

Establish monitoring systems: Social media listening tools (Mention, Brandwatch), Google Alerts for company and executive names, Customer support ticket analysis, Employee feedback channels, and Regulatory announcement monitoring.

Crisis simulation exercises: Run tabletop exercises quarterly, Simulate realistic crisis scenarios, Practice communication and decision-making, Identify gaps in preparedness, and Refine plans based on learnings.

Document and maintain: Keep crisis plans updated as company grows, Ensure new team members know their roles, and Review and refresh contact lists regularly.',
    '[{"task": "Complete a comprehensive risk assessment identifying top 10 crisis risks", "priority": "high"}, {"task": "Establish a crisis communication team with clear roles", "priority": "high"}, {"task": "Create holding statements for 5 most likely crisis scenarios", "priority": "medium"}, {"task": "Set up social media monitoring for brand mentions and sentiment", "priority": "medium"}]',
    '[{"title": "Mention Social Listening", "url": "https://mention.com/", "type": "tool"}, {"title": "Crisis Communication Planning Guide", "url": "https://www.prsa.org/", "type": "resource"}, {"title": "Brandwatch Analytics", "url": "https://www.brandwatch.com/", "type": "tool"}, {"title": "PRCAI (PR Council of India)", "url": "https://www.prcai.org/", "type": "association"}]'),

    (v_module_id, 'Crisis Response Execution', 'Execute effective communication during active crises.',
    'Managing communication when crises occur.', 2, 45,
    'When a crisis hits, the first 24 hours determine narrative control. Fast, transparent, empathetic communication limits damage; slow, defensive, or deceptive responses amplify it.

The crisis response sequence: Acknowledge (confirm you are aware of the issue), Investigate (gather facts before detailed response), Communicate (share what you know and do not know), Act (take concrete remedial steps), and Follow up (provide updates and resolution).

Initial response principles: Speed matters—acknowledge within hours, not days, Do not speculate—say "we are investigating" if facts are unclear, Express concern for affected stakeholders, Avoid blame-shifting or defensiveness, and Commit to transparency and updates.

Stakeholder communication priorities: Immediately affected parties (customers, employees directly impacted), Regulatory authorities (if required), Internal team (employees need information), Investors and board (for significant crises), Media (reactive and proactive), and General public (social media, website updates).

Message development during crisis: Lead with empathy (acknowledge impact on people), State the facts (what happened, what you know), Explain actions (what you are doing to fix it), Commit to prevention (how you will prevent recurrence), and Provide contact for questions.

Media management during crisis: Designate a single spokesperson, Brief spokesperson thoroughly on facts and boundaries, Prepare for tough questions and hostile interviews, Do not say "no comment"—explain what you can share, Correct inaccuracies quickly but calmly, and Document all media interactions.

Social media crisis response: Monitor constantly during active crisis, Respond to individual concerns with empathy, Do not delete negative comments (unless violating terms), Direct complex issues to private channels, and Post regular updates on resolution progress.

Common crisis response mistakes: Delayed acknowledgment, Appearing to hide information, Legalistic language lacking empathy, Blaming others or making excuses, Over-promising on timelines, and Declaring crisis over prematurely.',
    '[{"task": "Create crisis response playbooks for top 5 risk scenarios", "priority": "high"}, {"task": "Train primary and backup spokespersons on crisis communication", "priority": "high"}, {"task": "Develop stakeholder communication templates for crisis situations", "priority": "medium"}, {"task": "Establish rapid internal communication protocols for crisis activation", "priority": "medium"}]',
    '[{"title": "Crisis Communication Templates", "url": "https://www.smartsheet.com/crisis-communication-plan-templates", "type": "template"}, {"title": "Media Training Resources", "url": "https://www.mediafirst.co.uk/", "type": "training"}, {"title": "Hootsuite Crisis Response", "url": "https://www.hootsuite.com/", "type": "tool"}, {"title": "Sprout Social Crisis Guide", "url": "https://sproutsocial.com/", "type": "guide"}]'),

    (v_module_id, 'Reputation Recovery', 'Rebuild brand reputation after crisis events.',
    'Long-term recovery from brand damage.', 3, 40,
    'Crisis management does not end when immediate issues resolve. Reputation recovery is a long-term process requiring sustained effort to rebuild trust with stakeholders.

Post-crisis assessment: Document what happened and why, Analyze communication effectiveness, Identify what worked and what failed, Gather stakeholder feedback, and Calculate business impact (churn, revenue, sentiment).

Reputation recovery phases: Stabilization (immediate post-crisis, focus on resolution), Remediation (fixing underlying issues, demonstrating change), Rehabilitation (rebuilding trust through consistent action), and Renewal (returning to growth and forward-looking narrative).

Rebuilding trust requires action, not just communication: Fix the underlying problems that caused the crisis, Implement preventive measures visibly, Hold accountable parties responsible, Compensate affected stakeholders fairly, and Over-deliver on commitments made during crisis.

Communication during recovery: Share progress on promised actions, Highlight improvements and changes made, Earn third-party validation (awards, certifications, audits), Feature customer success stories and testimonials, and Gradually transition to forward-looking narratives.

Stakeholder-specific recovery: Customers—exceptional service, loyalty programs, direct outreach, Employees—transparent internal communication, address concerns, Investors—detailed recovery plans, progress reporting, Media—provide exclusive access to recovery story, and Regulators—demonstrate compliance and cooperation.

Monitoring recovery progress: Track sentiment trends over time, Monitor share of voice versus competitors, Survey stakeholder trust levels, Analyze customer retention and acquisition, and Watch for crisis recurrence signals.

Learning from crisis: Conduct formal post-mortem review, Update crisis plans based on learnings, Share learnings (appropriately) to demonstrate accountability, and Build organizational resilience for future challenges.

Recovery timeline expectations: Minor crises may recover in weeks, Major crises take months to years, Some reputation damage is permanent—focus on moving forward, and New positive associations must outweigh negative memories.',
    '[{"task": "Develop a reputation recovery plan template for post-crisis use", "priority": "high"}, {"task": "Create a stakeholder feedback mechanism to assess trust levels", "priority": "medium"}, {"task": "Establish reputation monitoring dashboards tracking sentiment over time", "priority": "medium"}, {"task": "Document crisis learnings process for organizational improvement", "priority": "medium"}]',
    '[{"title": "RepTrak Reputation Intelligence", "url": "https://www.reptrak.com/", "type": "tool"}, {"title": "Trust Barometer by Edelman", "url": "https://www.edelman.com/trust/", "type": "research"}, {"title": "Reputation Management Guide", "url": "https://www.reputationx.com/", "type": "guide"}, {"title": "Glassdoor Employer Brand", "url": "https://www.glassdoor.co.in/employers/", "type": "platform"}]');

    -- MODULE 7: Thought Leadership
    INSERT INTO modules (product_id, title, description, order_index, duration_days)
    VALUES (v_product_id, 'Thought Leadership', 'Establish founders and company as industry authorities.', 7, 5)
    RETURNING id INTO v_module_id;

    INSERT INTO lessons (module_id, title, description, content, order_index, duration_minutes, brief_content, action_items, resources) VALUES
    (v_module_id, 'Thought Leadership Strategy', 'Develop a strategic approach to building industry authority.',
    'Strategic framework for thought leadership.', 1, 45,
    'Thought leadership positions founders and companies as trusted authorities in their space. It attracts customers, investors, partners, and talent by demonstrating expertise and vision. For Indian startups competing for attention, thought leadership creates differentiation.

Thought leadership requires genuine expertise: You cannot manufacture thought leadership—it emerges from real knowledge, unique perspectives, and valuable insights. Identify where your experience provides perspectives others lack.

Defining your thought leadership territory: Industry trends and future predictions, Unique methodology or approach, Data and research from your business, Lessons from failures and successes, Policy perspectives and advocacy, and Technical deep dives in your domain.

The thought leadership content pyramid: Top (books, major keynotes, research reports)—rare, high-impact, Middle (articles, podcasts, panel appearances)—regular, moderate effort, Base (social media posts, comments, discussions)—frequent, low effort. Each tier feeds the others.

Identify your unique angle: What do you know that others do not? What contrarian views can you defend? What data do you have access to? What failures taught you valuable lessons? What predictions can you make about the future?

Platform selection for thought leadership: LinkedIn (B2B, professional audiences—essential in India), Twitter/X (real-time conversations, tech and startup communities), Medium or personal blog (long-form content ownership), Industry publications (earned credibility), and Podcasts (growing rapidly in India).

Thought leadership requires consistency: Publish regularly to build audience expectations, Maintain consistent themes while evolving perspectives, Balance promotion with genuine value delivery, and Engage with community, do not just broadcast.

Measure thought leadership impact: Follower growth and engagement rates, Inbound media requests, Speaking invitation frequency, Customer and talent acquisition attribution, and Industry recognition and awards.',
    '[{"task": "Define your thought leadership territory with 3-5 specific theme areas", "priority": "high"}, {"task": "Audit founder and company social presence identifying gaps", "priority": "high"}, {"task": "Create a 12-month thought leadership content calendar", "priority": "medium"}, {"task": "Identify 10 target platforms and publications for thought leadership", "priority": "medium"}]',
    '[{"title": "LinkedIn Creator Mode", "url": "https://www.linkedin.com/help/linkedin/answer/a522537", "type": "platform"}, {"title": "Medium Partner Program", "url": "https://medium.com/creators", "type": "platform"}, {"title": "Substack Newsletter Platform", "url": "https://substack.com/", "type": "platform"}, {"title": "Thought Leadership Research by Edelman", "url": "https://www.edelman.com/expertise/thought-leadership", "type": "research"}]'),

    (v_module_id, 'Content Creation for Authority', 'Create compelling content that establishes expertise.',
    'Building authority through content.', 2, 45,
    'Thought leadership content must provide genuine value—insights, frameworks, data, or perspectives audiences cannot easily find elsewhere. Quality trumps quantity; one exceptional piece outperforms dozens of mediocre posts.

Content types for thought leadership: Opinion pieces (your perspective on industry issues), How-to guides (share your methodology and expertise), Data and research (original insights from your business), Case studies (real examples with lessons learned), Predictions (where you see the industry heading), Responses (thoughtful commentary on others work), and Interviews (conversations with other experts).

Writing compelling thought leadership: Start with a strong, specific thesis, Support with evidence, examples, and data, Share personal experiences and failures, Acknowledge complexity and counterarguments, Conclude with actionable implications, and Write clearly—avoid jargon and corporate speak.

LinkedIn article best practices for India: Optimal length 800-1500 words for articles, Use clear subheadings for scannability, Include relevant hashtags (3-5 maximum), Post during weekday business hours IST, Engage with comments within first hour, and Share to relevant groups for amplification.

Building a content engine: Repurpose content across formats (article becomes video becomes podcast), Create content series building on themes, Collaborate with other thought leaders, Guest post on complementary platforms, and Use internal team expertise for content variety.

Ghostwriting considerations: Many executives use ghostwriters—this is acceptable, Ensure ghost-written content reflects genuine expertise, Review and approve everything before publication, Add personal touches and stories, and Gradually build capability to create independently.

Avoiding thought leadership pitfalls: Do not share competitors proprietary information, Avoid commenting on areas outside your expertise, Do not make predictions you cannot defend, Be careful with political and religious topics, and Maintain professional boundaries in content.',
    '[{"task": "Write and publish 3 foundational thought leadership articles", "priority": "high"}, {"task": "Develop a content repurposing workflow for efficiency", "priority": "medium"}, {"task": "Create a personal content voice guide for consistency", "priority": "medium"}, {"task": "Build a bank of content ideas covering 6 months of publishing", "priority": "high"}]',
    '[{"title": "Grammarly Writing Assistant", "url": "https://www.grammarly.com/", "type": "tool"}, {"title": "Canva for Social Graphics", "url": "https://www.canva.com/", "type": "tool"}, {"title": "YourStory Contributor Program", "url": "https://yourstory.com/about/contribute", "type": "publication"}, {"title": "Inc42 Guest Posts", "url": "https://inc42.com/write-for-us/", "type": "publication"}]'),

    (v_module_id, 'Speaking and Panel Opportunities', 'Secure speaking engagements that build authority.',
    'Public speaking for thought leadership.', 3, 40,
    'Speaking engagements provide powerful platforms for thought leadership—reaching engaged audiences, building credibility, and creating networking opportunities. For Indian startup founders, conference presence establishes authority.

Types of speaking opportunities: Keynote speeches (highest visibility, most competitive), Panel discussions (easier entry, shared spotlight), Fireside chats (conversational format, requires moderator skill), Workshop sessions (demonstrate expertise hands-on), Webinars (accessible, scalable reach), and Podcast interviews (growing importance, evergreen content).

Indian conference and event landscape: Major tech events: TechSparks, Inc42 Moneyball, TiEcon, NASSCOM events, Sector-specific: FinTech Festival, HealthTech Summit, SaaS events, Regional events: Startup Karnataka, Kerala Startup Mission events, and Corporate events: TED talks, industry association conferences.

Getting speaking invitations: Apply to open calls for speakers (watch event websites), Leverage existing relationships with organizers, Build reputation through smaller events first, Create compelling speaker profiles and topics, Offer unique angles organizers cannot get elsewhere, and Speakers bureaus for established thought leaders.

Speaking topic development: Identify topics matching both your expertise and audience interests, Create signature talks you can deliver repeatedly, Develop multiple talk options for different contexts, Update talks regularly with fresh examples and data, and Test and refine based on audience feedback.

Presentation skills for Indian audiences: Balance data with storytelling, Use relevant local examples and context, Respect time constraints precisely, Engage with Q&A thoughtfully, and Follow up with connections made.

Maximizing speaking opportunity value: Share announcement on social media before and after, Create content from presentation (video, slides, blog), Connect with other speakers and organizers, Collect attendee feedback for improvement, and Request testimonials and recording rights.',
    '[{"task": "Create a speaker profile with bio, headshot, and 3 talk topics", "priority": "high"}, {"task": "Identify and apply to 5 relevant speaking opportunities", "priority": "high"}, {"task": "Develop one signature talk with complete slides and script", "priority": "medium"}, {"task": "Practice presentation skills through internal presentations or Toastmasters", "priority": "medium"}]',
    '[{"title": "TechSparks by YourStory", "url": "https://yourstory.com/techsparks", "type": "event"}, {"title": "Inc42 Events", "url": "https://inc42.com/events/", "type": "event"}, {"title": "SpeakerHub", "url": "https://speakerhub.com/", "type": "platform"}, {"title": "TEDx India Events", "url": "https://www.ted.com/tedx/events", "type": "event"}]');

    -- MODULE 8: Social Media PR
    INSERT INTO modules (product_id, title, description, order_index, duration_days)
    VALUES (v_product_id, 'Social Media PR', 'Leverage social platforms for brand building and PR.', 8, 4)
    RETURNING id INTO v_module_id;

    INSERT INTO lessons (module_id, title, description, content, order_index, duration_minutes, brief_content, action_items, resources) VALUES
    (v_module_id, 'Social Media Strategy for PR', 'Develop social media strategies that support PR objectives.',
    'Integrating social media with PR strategy.', 1, 45,
    'Social media has fundamentally changed PR—news breaks on Twitter before wire services, journalists source stories from LinkedIn posts, and brand crises erupt from viral customer complaints. Effective PR now requires social media mastery.

Social media platform priorities for Indian startups: LinkedIn—essential for B2B, investor relations, thought leadership. Twitter/X—real-time news, journalist engagement, tech community. Instagram—consumer brands, visual storytelling, employer branding. YouTube—product demos, thought leadership videos, tutorials. WhatsApp—increasingly important for community and direct engagement.

Social media PR objectives: Build journalist relationships and visibility, Amplify traditional media coverage, Drive owned media distribution, Monitor brand mentions and sentiment, Respond to emerging issues quickly, and Create shareable content for earned amplification.

Content strategy for PR impact: News and announcements (share press releases with commentary), Behind-the-scenes content (humanize the company), Industry commentary (establish thought leadership), Customer success stories (proof of impact), Team and culture content (employer branding), and Engagement content (polls, questions, discussions).

Platform-specific best practices: LinkedIn—professional tone, long-form content, engage in comments. Twitter/X—real-time, conversational, hashtag usage, retweet with commentary. Instagram—visual quality, Stories for immediacy, Reels for reach. YouTube—SEO optimization, consistent publishing, playlist organization.

Social media voice should align with brand voice while adapting to platform norms. LinkedIn accepts formality; Twitter rewards wit and personality. Consistency in values, flexibility in expression.

Scheduling and consistency: Post regularly to maintain visibility (daily on Twitter, 3-5x/week on LinkedIn), Use scheduling tools for efficiency (Buffer, Hootsuite, Sprout), Balance scheduled content with real-time engagement, and Monitor analytics to optimize posting times.',
    '[{"task": "Audit current social media presence against PR objectives", "priority": "high"}, {"task": "Create platform-specific content strategies for top 3 channels", "priority": "high"}, {"task": "Develop a 4-week social media content calendar", "priority": "medium"}, {"task": "Set up social media scheduling and management tools", "priority": "medium"}]',
    '[{"title": "Buffer Social Media Management", "url": "https://buffer.com/", "type": "tool"}, {"title": "Hootsuite", "url": "https://www.hootsuite.com/", "type": "tool"}, {"title": "LinkedIn Marketing Solutions", "url": "https://business.linkedin.com/marketing-solutions", "type": "platform"}, {"title": "Twitter Business Resources", "url": "https://business.twitter.com/", "type": "platform"}]'),

    (v_module_id, 'Influencer and Community Engagement', 'Build relationships with influencers and online communities.',
    'Leveraging influencer relationships for PR.', 2, 40,
    'Influencers and online communities amplify brand messages to engaged audiences. In India, where digital communities are highly active, strategic influencer engagement extends PR reach significantly.

Influencer categories for B2B/startup PR: Industry analysts and experts, Prominent founders and investors, Business journalists and editors, Podcast hosts and content creators, LinkedIn Top Voices in your sector, and Twitter/X opinion leaders.

Identifying relevant influencers: Use tools like SparkToro, Followerwonk, or manual research, Look for engagement quality, not just follower counts, Prioritize relevance over reach, Check for authentic engagement versus bought followers, and Assess alignment with your brand values.

Influencer engagement approaches: Organic relationship building (engage genuinely over time), Paid partnerships (sponsored content, clear disclosure), Expert collaborations (joint content, research), Event partnerships (influencers speaking at your events), and Advisory relationships (formal advisory board roles).

Building genuine influencer relationships: Engage authentically with their content over time, Share their work with genuine appreciation, Offer value before asking for anything, Respect their time and expertise, and Maintain relationships beyond transactional needs.

Community engagement for PR: Identify communities where your audience participates (Slack groups, Discord servers, Reddit, Facebook groups), Participate authentically without constant promotion, Provide value through expertise and help, Build reputation within community before promotional activity, and Partner with community leaders for amplified reach.

Indian startup communities to consider: YourStory community, Inc42 Plus, Indian Startup Slack/Discord groups, Sector-specific WhatsApp groups, LinkedIn groups for your industry, and Alumni networks (IIM, IIT, etc.).

Measuring influencer and community impact: Track referral traffic from influencer mentions, Monitor brand mentions in target communities, Measure sentiment changes after influencer activities, and Calculate cost per engagement versus traditional PR.',
    '[{"task": "Identify 20 relevant influencers in your sector and research each", "priority": "high"}, {"task": "Begin genuine engagement with top 10 influencers", "priority": "high"}, {"task": "Map relevant online communities and join as active participant", "priority": "medium"}, {"task": "Develop an influencer relationship management tracker", "priority": "medium"}]',
    '[{"title": "SparkToro Audience Intelligence", "url": "https://sparktoro.com/", "type": "tool"}, {"title": "Followerwonk Twitter Analytics", "url": "https://followerwonk.com/", "type": "tool"}, {"title": "GRIN Influencer Platform", "url": "https://grin.co/", "type": "platform"}, {"title": "Indian Startup Community Directory", "url": "https://yourstory.com/", "type": "community"}]'),

    (v_module_id, 'Viral Content and Newsjacking', 'Create shareable content and leverage trending topics.',
    'Strategies for social media virality.', 3, 40,
    'Viral content and newsjacking can dramatically amplify brand visibility. While virality cannot be guaranteed, understanding what drives sharing and how to leverage news cycles improves PR impact.

What makes content shareable: Emotional resonance (joy, surprise, anger, inspiration), Practical value (useful information people want to share), Identity expression (content that reflects how people see themselves), Social currency (makes sharer look informed/clever), and Storytelling (narratives people want to pass along).

Viral content formats that work in India: Data visualizations with surprising findings, Relatable founder stories and failures, Industry predictions and hot takes, Behind-the-scenes and transparency content, Celebration of team and customer achievements, and Timely commentary on trending topics.

Newsjacking explained: Newsjacking involves inserting your brand into breaking news conversations. When relevant news breaks, quickly create content connecting your expertise to the story. Done well, it positions you as an authority; done poorly, it appears opportunistic.

Newsjacking best practices: Act quickly—relevance window is hours, not days, Ensure genuine connection to your expertise, Add value beyond obvious commentary, Be sensitive to crisis and tragedy contexts, and Have approval process that enables speed.

Indian newsjacking opportunities: Budget announcements (if relevant to your sector), Regulatory changes affecting your industry, Major funding rounds and exits, Policy announcements (Startup India, etc.), IPOs and market milestones, and Viral startup stories and debates.

Tools for trend monitoring: Google Trends India, Twitter Trending Topics, Reddit popular posts, LinkedIn trending articles, and Industry news aggregators.

Balancing planned and reactive content: Maintain content calendar for consistent publishing, Reserve capacity for reactive opportunities, Create templates for common reactive scenarios, and Do not sacrifice quality for speed.',
    '[{"task": "Create 3 pieces of content designed for shareability", "priority": "high"}, {"task": "Set up real-time monitoring for relevant news and trends", "priority": "high"}, {"task": "Develop newsjacking response templates for likely scenarios", "priority": "medium"}, {"task": "Establish rapid approval process for reactive content", "priority": "medium"}]',
    '[{"title": "Google Trends India", "url": "https://trends.google.co.in/", "type": "tool"}, {"title": "BuzzSumo Content Research", "url": "https://buzzsumo.com/", "type": "tool"}, {"title": "Twitter Trending India", "url": "https://twitter.com/explore/tabs/trending", "type": "platform"}, {"title": "Newsjacking Book by David Meerman Scott", "url": "https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/13589182-newsjacking", "type": "book"}]');

    -- MODULE 9: Awards and Recognition
    INSERT INTO modules (product_id, title, description, order_index, duration_days)
    VALUES (v_product_id, 'Awards and Recognition', 'Win awards that build credibility and visibility.', 9, 4)
    RETURNING id INTO v_module_id;

    INSERT INTO lessons (module_id, title, description, content, order_index, duration_minutes, brief_content, action_items, resources) VALUES
    (v_module_id, 'Awards Strategy Development', 'Develop a strategic approach to pursuing relevant awards.',
    'Building an awards strategy that delivers ROI.', 1, 45,
    'Awards provide third-party validation that builds credibility with customers, investors, and partners. For Indian startups, strategic award pursuit accelerates brand building. However, awards require investment—be strategic about which to pursue.

Award categories relevant to Indian startups: Startup awards (YourStory Tech30, Inc42 30 Under 30, TiE awards), Industry awards (sector-specific recognition), Business awards (ET Awards, Business World recognition), Innovation awards (CII Industrial Innovation, NASSCOM awards), Regional awards (state-level startup recognition), and Global awards (Deloitte Technology Fast 50, Forbes lists).

Evaluating award opportunities: Credibility of awarding body, Relevance to your target audience, Past winner quality and reputation, Application effort versus recognition value, Cost (entry fees, event attendance), and Timeline alignment with your PR calendar.

Application best practices: Start early—most applications take longer than expected, Follow instructions precisely and completely, Use specific metrics and evidence, Tell compelling stories, not just facts, Get applications reviewed by multiple people, and Keep records for reuse in future applications.

Building an awards calendar: Map relevant awards throughout the year, Note application deadlines (typically 2-3 months before announcement), Plan submission timing to avoid last-minute rush, Track results and iterate approach, and Allocate budget for entry fees and events.

Award categories to prioritize early: Emerging company and startup categories, Young entrepreneur and founder awards, Innovation and technology awards, and Regional and sector-specific recognition. As you grow, target broader business and leadership awards.

Maximizing award win value: Issue press release announcing wins, Update website, email signatures, and materials, Share on social media with genuine appreciation, Display awards visibly in office and presentations, Reference awards in sales and investor conversations, and Thank nominators and selection committees publicly.

Managing award losses: Not winning is normal—persistence matters, Seek feedback where available, Refine applications based on learnings, and Continue building relationships with award organizations.',
    '[{"task": "Research and list 20 relevant awards for your company stage and sector", "priority": "high"}, {"task": "Create an awards calendar with deadlines for the next 12 months", "priority": "high"}, {"task": "Develop a master award application document with key metrics and stories", "priority": "medium"}, {"task": "Apply to 3 awards this quarter with strong applications", "priority": "medium"}]',
    '[{"title": "YourStory Tech30", "url": "https://yourstory.com/tech30", "type": "award"}, {"title": "Inc42 30 Under 30", "url": "https://inc42.com/", "type": "award"}, {"title": "TiE Awards", "url": "https://tie.org/", "type": "award"}, {"title": "CII Industrial Innovation Awards", "url": "https://www.cii.in/", "type": "award"}]'),

    (v_module_id, 'Application Excellence', 'Create winning award applications that stand out.',
    'Crafting compelling award submissions.', 2, 40,
    'Award applications are competitive—judges review dozens or hundreds of submissions. Winning requires applications that clearly communicate achievement, tell compelling stories, and meet evaluation criteria precisely.

Understanding award criteria: Carefully read all evaluation criteria, Weight your application toward stated priorities, If criteria are unclear, ask organizers for guidance, and Study past winners for patterns.

Application components typically include: Executive summary (compelling overview), Company background (context and positioning), Achievement description (what you accomplished), Impact evidence (metrics and outcomes), Supporting materials (documentation, testimonials), and Future vision (where you are heading).

Writing compelling achievement narratives: Start with the problem you solved, Describe your unique approach, Quantify results with specific metrics, Include before/after comparisons, Feature customer voices and testimonials, and Explain why this matters beyond your company.

Metrics that impress judges: Revenue growth (percentage and absolute), Customer acquisition and retention, Market share gains, Efficiency improvements, Social impact measures, and Innovation indicators (patents, firsts, breakthroughs).

Common application mistakes: Missing deadlines (no exceptions typically), Exceeding word or page limits, Generic content not tailored to criteria, Unsubstantiated claims without evidence, Poor formatting and presentation, and Submitting incomplete applications.

Application review process: Have multiple people review applications, Check for clarity, completeness, and persuasion, Verify all facts and figures, Test links and attachments, Review against evaluation criteria, and Allow time for revision before deadline.

Building relationships with award organizations: Attend their events even before applying, Volunteer as judges for other categories, Connect with organizers on LinkedIn, Sponsor events where budget allows, and Provide testimonials if asked.',
    '[{"task": "Analyze 5 winning applications from relevant awards", "priority": "high"}, {"task": "Create a template application with reusable company content", "priority": "high"}, {"task": "Compile a metrics and evidence library for applications", "priority": "medium"}, {"task": "Establish an internal review process for award submissions", "priority": "medium"}]',
    '[{"title": "Economic Times Awards", "url": "https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/et-awards", "type": "award"}, {"title": "Deloitte Technology Fast 50 India", "url": "https://www2.deloitte.com/in/en/pages/technology-media-and-telecommunications/articles/technology-fast-50-india.html", "type": "award"}, {"title": "Forbes India Lists", "url": "https://www.forbesindia.com/lists/", "type": "award"}, {"title": "NASSCOM Awards", "url": "https://nasscom.in/", "type": "award"}]'),

    (v_module_id, 'Leveraging Recognition', 'Maximize the value of awards and recognition.',
    'Turning award wins into business impact.', 3, 40,
    'Winning an award is just the beginning—maximum value comes from strategic amplification and integration into your brand narrative. Many companies under-leverage their wins.

Immediate win amplification: Issue press release within 24-48 hours of announcement, Post across all social media platforms, Email announcement to customers and partners, Update website homepage and about page, Add to email signatures company-wide, and Notify investors with congratulations update.

Press release for award wins: Headline featuring award name and your company, Quote from founder on what win means, Brief description of award credibility, Description of what you won for, Context on competitive field if impressive, and Boilerplate and contact information.

Long-term integration: Add award logos to website footer and materials, Include in investor deck and sales presentations, Reference in company boilerplate, Feature in trade show displays and signage, Update LinkedIn company page, and Include in recruiting materials.

Award event attendance: Attend ceremonies when possible for networking, Prepare acceptance remarks if speaking, Document with photos and video, Live-post during events, and Connect with fellow winners and judges.

Creating content from wins: Write blog post sharing lessons behind the win, Create case study format content, Develop social media content series, Produce video thanking team and customers, and Pitch follow-up stories to media.

Award logo usage guidelines: Follow award organization brand guidelines, Use current year version only (or clearly date), Do not modify award logos, Maintain minimum size requirements, and Retire logos after reasonable timeframe (typically 2-3 years).

Building momentum from wins: Use credibility to pursue larger opportunities, Leverage for speaking engagement invitations, Reference in future award applications, and Build relationships with judges and organizers.',
    '[{"task": "Create a standard amplification checklist for award wins", "priority": "high"}, {"task": "Develop templates for award announcement press releases and social posts", "priority": "high"}, {"task": "Update all company materials with recent award recognition", "priority": "medium"}, {"task": "Build a relationships tracker for award organizations and judges", "priority": "medium"}]',
    '[{"title": "Award Logo Usage Guidelines", "url": "https://www.aiga.org/", "type": "guide"}, {"title": "Canva Award Badge Templates", "url": "https://www.canva.com/templates/?query=award+badge", "type": "template"}, {"title": "Press Release Templates", "url": "https://www.prnewswire.com/resources/", "type": "template"}, {"title": "LinkedIn Company Page Updates", "url": "https://business.linkedin.com/", "type": "platform"}]');

    -- MODULE 10: Community Building
    INSERT INTO modules (product_id, title, description, order_index, duration_days)
    VALUES (v_product_id, 'Community Building', 'Build engaged communities around your brand.', 10, 5)
